{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"794b7ed4-1fd7-425b-89d5-7782e8410278","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Required: marks the project as a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n\n  <!-- The command users will run (e.g., `dotnet tool install -g my-mcp-server`) -->\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet package metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n\n  <!-- Must be exe for stdio transport -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key steps:**\n\n1. **`PackAsTool = true`** — this is the critical setting that makes `dotnet pack` produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command name after installation.\n3. **`OutputType` = `Exe`** — required for stdio-based MCP servers.\n4. **Pack & publish:**\n   ```bash\n   dotnet pack -c Release\n   dotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n     --api-key YOUR_API_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n   ```\n5. **Users install with:**\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\n   ```\n\nThat's all that's needed — no custom packaging or manifest files required.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fd505607-fcb6-4265-9104-82cc524c923b","outputTokens":460,"requestId":"5C40:48F1C:1D417F0:2064C94:69FA940F"},"id":"37a243b7-b855-4ecd-8a4b-ee9d562e8d0a","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:06:34.398Z","parentId":"6105c64d-fdce-48bc-9a83-2f1b034ffe9c"}
